1.Describe the difference between visual contrast andluminance? Why do retinal ganglion cells encodecontrast instead of luminance?

  1. Describe the difference between visual contrast andluminance? Why do retinal ganglion cells encodecontrast instead of luminance?
  2. vision: luminance is the light intensity per unit area agiven direction. Contrast of luminance is the localdifference in luminance between adjacent regions.

Retinal ganglion cells encode contrast to

  1. Cope with large variation in ambient light intensity.
  2. To encode information efficiently–mostinformation about objects is present in contrastrather than intensity.

2.What is meant by topographic organisation in sensorynervous systems.

Topographic organisation occurs when neuronsneighbouring locations of a part of the nervous systemtunned to respond to stimuli with similar, but differentproperties.

2.Which sensory systems considered in lectures displaya topographic organisation?

The somatosensory, auditory and visual systems alldisplay topographic representation of their sensorysurfaces.

  1. Why is seizure forecasting important? Describe 2-3key challenges that must be considered in thedevelopment of seizure forecasting technology.
  1. Why is seizure forecasting important? Describe 2-3 keychallenges that must be considered in the developmentof seizure forecasting technology.

Points for importance:

  • People with epilepsy consistently report that the unpredictability ofseizures is the most debilitating aspect of their condition
  • Unpredictable seizures may be dangerous / life threatening (i.e.,activities such as driving, cooking, swimming, bike ridingetcmay all beoff limits if you don’t know when a seizure will happen)
  • Forecasts can enable treatment (such as medication dosage) to beadjusted for high-risk times, potentially reducing the amount ofmedication people need to take. For many people, anti-seizure drugshave bad side effects such as dizziness, nausea, confusion, weight gain /lossetcso using less medication can improve their quality of life
  • Similarly, DBS (or other neural stimulators) to treat seizures are often‘always on’. Reducing the amount of stimulation during low-risk periodswould conserve battery life of these devices and reduce the number ofbrain surgeries required for battery replacement
  1. Why is seizure forecasting important? Describe 2-3 keychallenges that must be considered in the development ofseizure forecasting technology.

Key challenges:

  • Patient-specific / individual specific:The patterns and risk factors ofseizures differ greatly between individuals. For instance, somepeople may experience a strong circadian effect, whereas othershave a 9-day or monthly rhythm. Similarly, risk factors such as poorsleep affect people differently. i.e., even though we know sleep isvery important some people’s seizures may be triggered by a latebedtime whereas others may be triggered by oversleeping or havingtoo little REM sleep. This is probably because everyone’s seizuresstart for different reasons and from different brain regions. Soforecasts have to bepersonalisedfor everyone, which means thatenough data must be collected for each persons’ seizures in order tobuild up a good model of their seizure likelihood.
  • 
  1. Why is seizure forecasting important? Describe 2-3key challenges that must be considered in thedevelopment of seizure forecasting technology.

Key challenges:

  • Rare events:For some people, seizures may only occurseveral times per month or even per year (incidentallythese individuals with relatively infrequent seizures aremost likely to benefit from forecasting), resulting in verylimited training data for forecasting algorithms. Manyclassic machine learning algorithms / AI are not so usefulwhen there are only a handful of training examples.
  1. Why is seizure forecasting important? Describe 2-3 keychallenges that must be considered in the developmentof seizure forecasting technology.

Key challenges:

  • Unknown cause (brain models are all “bad” and we’re stillworking out when they’re useful):Although ML models arechallenged by limited data, physiological models of seizureonset are also difficult to develop, and we do not have arobust model of how macroscopic brain activity (such as EEG)is generated or how seizures arise. This is quite unlikeforecasting extreme weather events (for instance), wherethere are well-validated meteorological models to help withextrapolating what will happen next based on a range ofmeasurements..
  1. Why is seizure forecasting important? Describe 2-3 keychallenges that must be considered in the developmentof seizure forecasting technology.

Key challenges:

  • Long-term recording (i.e., chronic):Device must be able to beused long-term and not be overlystigmatisingor interfere withthe user’s life too greatly. Scalp electrodes (even “wearable”dry electrode caps or headbands) are not practical for lifetimeuse. Many other neuroimaging techniques such as fMRI,fNIRS,are not portable. Implantable electrodes involve varyingdegrees of surgical risk. Wearable devices do not directlymonitor brain or seizure activity.
  1. Why is seizure forecasting important? Describe 2-3 keychallenges that must be considered in the development ofseizure forecasting technology.

Key challenges:

  • Perfect predictability is impossible.There is always somerandomness (or unmeasured quantities) that influence the brain’sstate and may cause seizures. That is why we refer to “forecasting”of “seizure likelihood” rather than “prediction” of “seizureoccurrence”. For instance, a person could be in a very low risk stateyet happen to receive some sudden environmental input that causesa seizure. Can people with epilepsy understand and accept aforecast that is displayed as a likelihood and still leaves room foruncertainty? Probably some people can, and some cannot. Goodengineers willrecognisethat considering the design and userexperience from an early stage is critical to the success of any newtechnology, including seizure forecasts.

1.Briefly describe the following three routes taken bypreganglionic neurons of the sympathetic nervous systemstarting from the cell body.

  1. Spinal nerve route: cell body-> communicating rami(white tract)-> paravertebral ganglion/sympatheticganglion->postganglionic neuron
  2. Sympathetic chain ganglia route: cell body->communicating rami (white tract)-> paravertebralganglion/sympathetic ganglion->sympathetic ganglionchain (ascending and descending)->postganglionicneuron
  3. Splanchnic nerve route: cell body-> communicatingrami (white tract)-> paravertebral ganglion/sympatheticganglion->prevetebral/collateral ganglion->postganglionic neuron
